1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 { This is the most flexible move for 
White. He keeps his options open of developing his knight either on e2 or f3. Another 
recent idea of this move is to play Qd1-d2 and then fianchetto his bishop to b2 
after b2-b3.} (5. e4 {should more or less transpose to positions arising in the 
mainline after 5.d3. This is so because at some point White has to play d2-d3. For 
example,} e6 6. Nge2 Nge7 7. 0-0 0-0 8. d3 d6 {Transposes} ) d6 {We wait for White 
to show his cards and then react accordingly.} 6. e4 { This is by far the main move 
in this position for White. He prepares to develop his knight with Ng1-e2 and then 
go for o-o. By putting his pawn on e4 instead of e3 White prevents Black's e6-d5 
pawn break in the centre (which can be seen in chapter 4 where Black goes for the 
e6-d5 break) , but the drawback is that it weakens the d4-square which can be used 
by Black's pieces.} (6. Nf3 {White prepares to o-o, but by developing his knight 
to f3 White has also blocked the h1-a8 diagonal and the c6 knight is no longer attacked 
by the White bishop. Therefore we should play,} Rb8 $5 { with the idea to break 
on the queenside with ...a6 and then ...b5. Now after,} 7. 0-0 {we transpose to 
Chapter 5.} ) (6. Qd2 $5 { This is the main reason why 5.d3 has become a trending 
option for White nowadays. White supports his c3-knight thus making it possible 
to play b2-b3 and then Bc1-b2. By bringing his bishop on the long diagonal White 
hopes to challenge Black's dark square bishop in the future by moving his knight 
away from c3.} Nf6 {I like this active way of playing in this position. Playing 
6..Nf6 helps Black to o-o and also delays the exchange of the dark square bishops 
as the knight blocks the a1-h8 diagonal.} 7. b3 0-0 8. Bb2 e6 { preparing to take 
action in the centre with ...d5. After only 8 moves we have entered unchartered 
territory as there are only 3 games played from this position.} 9. e3 {This was 
the choice of Aronian.} (9. Nf3 {White prepares to o-o.} d5 $146 {a logical follow-up 
to 8...e6.} (9... Bd7 {1-0 (19) Dos Santos,M (2363) -Gandolfo,H (2189) CADAP corr 
2002} ) 10. 0-0 Qe7 { vacating the d8-square for the rook.} 11. e3 Rd8 12. cxd5 
exd5 13. Rac1 Bg4 $1 {Black intends to eliminate the f3-knight thus getting a better 
hold on the central squares.} 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Rac8 { Black is doing good and 
is ready to break in the centre with d5-d4. If White decides to prevent it with} 
16. d4 {then Black can play,} cxd4 17. exd4 Ne4 $15 $1 { creating pressure on the 
d4-pawn and also placing the knight on the powerful central e4-square. The knight 
on e4 can be further strengthened with ....f5.} ) d5 10. Nge2 d4 $146 $1 { A novelty 
and according to me the best move that gives Black some chances to seize the initiative. 
By advancing d5-d4 and gaining more space in the centre we may enter a Benoni-type 
structure with reversed colours. In these types of structure, the bishop on b2 is 
not ideally placed.} (10... dxc4 {1/2-1/2 (21) Aronian,L (2773) -Areshchenko,A (2678) 
Karlsruhe GER 2020} ) 11. Na4 { White puts pressure on both the c5 and the d4 pawns.} 
(11. exd4 $6 {committing to this pawn exchange may not be such a good idea. For 
example,} cxd4 12. Nb5 { it seems White can generate counterplay based on the attack 
on the d4-pawn and the idea of Bb2-a3, but things are not so easy for White. After 
the simple,} e5 13. Ba3 Ne8 $1 { a nice surprising idea! Black covers the d6-square 
and gets ready to kick the White knight from b5 with a7-a6. There is no need to 
fear losing the exchange because after,} (13... Re8 $2 14. Nd6 Re6 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 
16. 0-0 $11 {When the position is more or less balanced.} ) 14. Bxf8 Bxf8 { The 
dual threats of Bf8-b4 and a7-a6 are impossible for White to meet.} 15. 0-0 a6 $17 
{ the knight is trapped and Black gets two pieces for the rook.} ) (11. Ne4 {is 
simply met by,} Nxe4 12. Bxe4 e5 $15 { When Black is slightly better due to more 
space in the centre.} ) Qd6 { Black would like to play ...e5 next and strengthen 
his centre.} (11... Nd7 $6 {is passive as after,} 12. 0-0 $14 { Black experiences 
development problems.} ) 12. Ba3 { now both the d4 and c5 pawns are under threat. 
This forces Black to exchange on e3 but there is no problem is playing ...dxe3 as 
White too wasted a few moves (Na4 and Ba3) to make this happen.} dxe3 13. fxe3 b6 
$15 { Black is ready to play ...Bb7 and ...Rad8 with pressure on the d-file. Black 
has more space and his pieces are harmoniously placed. So, Black is slightly better. 
If White tries to eliminate his d-pawn weakness with,} 14. d4 {then Black can simply 
