1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e3 { With this move White makes it clear 
that he wants to develop his knight on e2. Another point behind playing e2-e3 is 
that he can later break in the centre with d2-d4.} e6 { We will follow the same 
strategy and I believe this to be the most solid way to face the 5.e3 variation.} 
6. Nge2 { The logical continuation to 5.e3. White prepares o-o.} (6. b3 $5 { This 
is an interesting idea introduced recently by Kramnik. White wants to develop his 
bishop quickly to a3, attacking the c5-pawn, and then continue developing his kingside. 
But it also allows Black to break in the centre immediately...} d5 $146 $1 {Black 
