1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 e6 6. a3 { A prophylactic move 
intending to prevent ...Bb4 so that White can play e2-e4 next without worrying about 
the pin on the c3-knight.} Be7 {Black simply develops the bishop and prepares to 
0-0.} 7. e4 0-0 8. Nf3 { It may seem strange to retreat the knight from d4 when 
White should be focusing on his development. But the idea behind playing Nd4-f3 
is to prevent the ...d5 break. If Black gets the ...d5 break comfortably then he 
will be able to free his position and White will lose his space advantage.} (8. 
Be2 {allows the obvious,} d5 $1 {Black gets the ...d5 break in the centre without 
working hard for it.} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. 
0-0 Bf6 14. Bf3 Be6 $11 {and it is obvious that Black is already doing quite fine. 
White has some pressure on the d5 pawn for now but Black has pressure against the 
b2-pawn. 0-1 (59) Lodici,L (2463) -Delchev,A (2563) Brixen Bressanone ITA 2019} 
) (8. Nc2 {This is another way to prevent the ...d5 break. But the knight is comparatively 
passive on c2 than on f3 and needs to be brought back in the game with Nc2-e3 at 
some point.} b6 { fianchettoing the bishop is the best way to develop the light 
square bishop as from b7 it can also put pressure on the e4-pawn.} 9. Be2 Bb7 10. 
0-0 Na5 $1 { it is odd to voluntarily shift the knight on the edge of the board, 
but here it works concretely for Black. By moving the knight to a5 Black not only 
threatens to capture the e4-pawn but also intends to play ... Nb3 winning the bishop 
pair.} 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 { ...Nb3 is going to come next.} 13. Bf4 $146 {is 
the most logical way to avoid losing the bishop pair and increasing control over 
the d6 break.} (13. Ne3 {has been White's choice in the games played from this position.} 
d6 $146 $1 {It is good for Black to open up the position as quickly as possible 
since White's pieces are un-coordinated right now.} (13... Qc7 {0-1 (47) Santiago,Y 
(2479) -Macieja, B (2513) Merida MEX 2019} ) 14. b4 Nc6 $17 {Black stands clearly 
better as his pieces are in harmony compared to white's.} ) Nb3 14. Ra2 d6 $1 {using 
tactics to achieve the desired break.} 15. exd6 Bxd6 16. Bxd6 Bxc2 17. Qxc2 Nd4 
$1 {a nice intermediate move.} 18. Qd3 Qxd6 $15 { the knight placed in the centre 
is of course stronger than White's bishop. Black would like to bring his rooks into 
